'''Yevgeny Ivanovich Nosov''' ({{lang-ru|Евгений Иванович Носов}}; January 15,
[[1925 in literature|1925]] in [[Kursk]], [[USSR]] &ndash; June 13, [[2002 in literature|2002]] in Kursk, [[Russian Federation]]) was a Soviet [[Russian literature|Russian writer]], part of the [[village prose]] movement, who since 1958 (when he debuted with ''On the Fisherman's Trail'', a collection of stories and short novels) contributed regularly to ''[[Nash Sovremennik]]'' and ''[[Novy Mir]]'' magazines. Nosov, who fought in [[World War II]] and was severely injured in February 1945, received two [[Order of Lenin|Orders of Lenin]] (1984, 1990) and the [[Hero of the Socialist Labour]] (1990) title. In 2001 he was awarded the [[Solzhenitsyn Prize]] for having created works that "...highlighted the tragedy of the War and the immense consequences it had for the Russian village, revealed to the full extent the belated bitterness of forgotten and neglected war veterans."<ref name="WW2">{{cite web | author = | date = | url  = http://wwii-soldat.narod.ru/200/ARTICLES/BIO/nosov_ei.htm|title = Nosov, Yevgeny Ivanovich| publisher  = wwii-soldat.narod.ru| accessdate = 2014-01-13}}</ref><ref name="kursk">{{cite web | author = | date = | url  = http://kurskonb.ru/our-booke/site/persons/en.html|title = Evgeny Nosov biography | publisher  = Kursk Science Library // The Literary Map of the Kursk Krai| accessdate = 2014-01-13}}</ref>

